{"title":"Cloud-Device Collaborative Adaptation to Continual Changing Environments in the Real-world","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Lightweight models deployed on devices degrade under continual distribution shifts and cannot be frequently updated due to limited on-device compute and uplink bandwidth.","method":"Introduce Cloud-Device Collaborative Continual Adaptation with Uncertainty Guided Sampling (UGS) that selects and uploads only the most environment-specific/OOD samples. UGS estimates uncertainty via Monte Carlo Dropout by computing the variance of repeated detection class probabilities and transmits samples whose uncertainty exceeds a threshold. The cloud updates a teacher–student detector on these challenging samples and returns adapted parameters, achieving similar or better performance with far less data (e.g., outperforming full-data training using only ~42–50% of samples) and beating random selection while reducing bandwidth."},{"problem":"Transferring the generalization of a large cloud model to a lightweight device model under continual shifts while keeping downlink bandwidth low and mitigating catastrophic forgetting.","method":"Propose a Visual Prompt Learning Strategy with Uncertainty-Guided Updating (VPLU): learn pixel-level visual prompts added to input images (used in both cloud training and on-device inference) to pull the device test distribution closer to cloud training. Prompts are updated with an uncertainty-aware EMA where the update weight increases with sample uncertainty, and are combined with adversarial feature alignment on the teacher (domain discriminator + GRL) and pseudo-label knowledge transfer to the student (high-confidence filtering). Only prompts (~0.4% of model parameters) and the lightweight student are sent to devices, yielding consistent gains (e.g., +3.3% over pseudo-label baseline; +2.7% from U-EMA) and alleviating forgetting across continual domains."}]}
